  "prompt": "Why can't your switch statement data type be long, Java?",
  "response": "In Java, prior to Java 7, the switch statement only supported certain data types: byte, short, char, int, and their corresponding wrapper classes (Byte, Short, Character, Integer). Starting with Java 7, the switch statement was extended to support String, and in Java 12, it was further enhanced with pattern matching for switch statements.\n\nThe limitation on long data types in switch statements is primarily due to historical design decisions and performance considerations:\n\n1. Historical Implementation:\n   - The switch statement was originally designed to work efficiently with integer-based types\n   - Long values require more complex comparisons compared to int\n\n2. Performance Reasons:\n   - Integer-based switch statements can be implemented using more efficient jump tables\n   - Long comparisons would require more complex and slower comparison logic\n\n3. Implementation Complexity:\n   - Supporting long would require additional runtime overhead for comparisons\n   - The JVM's switch instruction is optimized for int-sized values\n\nIf you need to use long values in a switch-like construct, you can:\n1. Use if-else statements\n2. Convert long to int (with potential loss of information)\n3. Use alternative design patterns\n\nExample alternative:\n```java\nswitch ((int)myLongValue) {\n    case 1:\n        // Handle\n        break;\n    // Other cases\n}\n```\n\nOr use a more flexible approach:\n```java\nif (myLongValue == 1L) {\n    // Handle\n} else if (myLongValue == 2L) {\n    // Handle\n}\n```",
